Plz explain why high temps = calf tightness

Generally higher temperatures are associated with your muscles being looser, because the heat opens up blood vessels bringing more oxygen and helping to take away lactic acid and thus technically decreasing soreness. which is why most athletes, especially fast twitch muscle athlete's don't need to warm up as much in the heat, and why at physical therapy they put hot pads on you before starting therapy. I would say muscle soreness might be more from trying to maintain the same expected pace or effort in the heat. But i mean who knows muscle soreness can stem from millions of different things, just be sure to not kill yourself for two weeks again pls

If your foot still hurts but you still want to do a workout I'd say theres two options. 1. Go slow on an easy run to let your foot recover and then try to do a workout the next day, maybe an abbreviated one or the 1' repeats so you can stop if need be easily.  2. Do a tempo. Tempos are good because you dont go as fast = less stress on foot, and since its continuous unlike the workout,  you still get a good benefit. My vote would be a tempo.
